table2.Title: From TV Animation Slam Dunk: Dream Team Shueisha Limited
table2.Notes: This is a prize version of the retail game From TV Animation Slam Dunk: Yonkyo Taiketsu!!.  It differs from the retail release featuring all-star teams, however the story mode was removed. It was given away though the shōnen manga comic Weekly Shōnen Jump.

table2.Title: JR West Presents Super Momotarō Dentetsu DX
table2.Notes: This version was given away by the railway company JR West.  The starting point is Osaka instead of Tokyo.

table2.Title: Kunio-kun no Dodgeball da yo Zen'in Shūgō Tournament Special
table2.Notes: This version has no single player mode, it only supports 2 players. Technōs Japan held several tournaments and the winners received the game as a gold cartridge trophy.

table2.Title: Magical Drop 2 Bunka Housou Special Version
table2.Notes: This version was linked with the Japanese radio program Terumi Yoshida Yaoruki No Mama!  It includes a team of the JOQR Japanese radio station, including the radio presenter Terumi Yoshida [ja].

table2.Title: Motoko-chan no Wonder Kitchen
table2.Notes: This game was given away through a mail-in contest.

table2.Title: Pachinko Tetsujin: Shichiban Shoubu
table2.Notes: This was given away as a Pachinko prize.

table2.Title: Super Bomberman 2 Taikenban
table2.Notes: A gold cartridge given as a prize for a Hi-Ten Bomberman tournament at a Hudson All-Japan Caravan Festival.

table2.Title: Super Bomberman 5 CoroCoro Comic
table2.Notes: A gold cartridge given away though the kodomo manga comic CoroCoro Comic.

table2.Title: Super Formation Soccer 95: della Serie A: UCC Xaqua
table2.Notes: This was given away through a competition where participants entered via mail.  The version features the 1993 FIFA World Player of the Year Roberto Baggio, and Xaqua sports drink branding.

table2.Title: Super Tetris 2 + Bombliss: Gentei-ban
table2.Notes: This limited edition has a contest mode with 60 new levels, a puzzle mode with 150 new puzzles, new music, jingles and background graphics.  It was later re-released in 1997 for general sale.

table2.Title: Tengai Makyō Zero: Shōnen Jump no Shou
table2.Notes: This was given away though the shōnen manga comic Weekly Shōnen Jump.

table2.Title: UFO Kamen Yakisoban: Kettler no Kuroi Inbō - Keihin Ban
table2.Notes: This is the original version for which Nissin ran a draw allowing buyers of their Yakisoba UFO [ja] cup noodles to win a copy of the game.  It was later released for general sale with some changes.  This version includes in-game Nissin branding and a congratulatory message.  The box art includes photos of actors of the TV series rather than illustrations.

table2.Title: UNDAKE 30 Shark Turtle Operation: Mario Version
table2.Notes: This was originally planned for retail however its release was postponed before being cancelled and was then used as prize for a high-score contest.  Also released digitally for the Satellaview.

table2.Title: Yoshi no Cookie: Kuruppon Oven de Cookie
table2.Notes: This was given away as a contest prize to promote National's NE-KC77 microwave oven.

table5.Title: Assault Suits Valken Declassified
table5.undefined: The Cybernator release from 1993 was censored in western regions.  This relocalised release is the original Japanese version translated in English.[13]

table5.Title: Magical Drop II
table5.undefined: A previously unreleased English localisation from 1996. Not to be confused with the English localisation of the game found in the Data East Classics Collection cartridge released in 2018 for the Super NES.[14]

table5.Title: River City Girls Zero
table5.undefined: An English localisation of Shin Nekketsu Kōha: Kunio-tachi no Banka developed by WayForward and Arc System Works. Also released later for PlayStation 4, PlayStation 5, Windows, Xbox One and Xbox Series X/S on September 21, 2022.[15]

table5.Title: Star Fox 2
table5.Platform: Super Nintendo Entertainment System Classic Edition
table5.undefined: The development of this game was completed in 1995 but it was cancelled.  Also released later on Nintendo Switch Online in 2019.

table5.Title: Trials of Mana
table5.undefined: A North American release had been planned during the console's lifespan but was cancelled due to bugs that they deemed impossible to fix in a timely manner. Released as part of Collection of Mana.[16]
